1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.100


2
00:00:01.100 --> 00:00:07.133
Audit, usage, and user data can answer some of the most important questions about Microsoft 365

3
00:00:07.133 --> 00:00:12.866
and Copilot adoption. But getting that data repeatedly is where the friction starts.

4
00:00:12.866 --> 00:00:14.199


5
00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:20.466
The portals are great for interactive review. But when you need repeatable exports for dashboards

6
00:00:20.466 --> 00:00:26.466
and analysis, manual steps add up fast. And scripted exports bring their

7
00:00:26.466 --> 00:00:26.499


8
00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:32.933
own setup work. Dates. Paths. Auth options. Switches. Output folders.

9
00:00:32.933 --> 00:00:33.066


10
00:00:33.066 --> 00:00:39.166
Permissions. Command syntax. That setup should not be the hardest part of getting

11
00:00:39.166 --> 00:00:39.199


12
00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:45.200
to insight. That is why PAX exists. PAX gives teams a

13
00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:51.400
powerful PowerShell engine for audit and user data exports, without forcing every team to piece together

14
00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:51.433


15
00:00:51.433 --> 00:00:57.566
export logic from scratch. PAX brings the engine. But someone still

16
00:00:57.566 --> 00:01:02.699
has to build the right command. That is where PAX Cookbook Mini-Kitchen comes in.

17
00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:03.900


18
00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:10.033
Mini-Kitchen is a guided browser-only command builder for PAX. It helps you choose the

19
00:01:10.033 --> 00:01:10.066


20
00:01:10.066 --> 00:01:16.499
right recipe, review the options, and create a copy-ready command. Start with a dashboard

21
00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:22.700
recipe. For example, the AI-in-One dashboard preset gives you a practical starting

22
00:01:22.700 --> 00:01:22.733


23
00:01:22.733 --> 00:01:28.833
point for a real reporting workflow. From there, Mini-Kitchen guides the command

24
00:01:28.833 --> 00:01:34.299
setup step-by-step. Choose the scenario. Set the date range.

25
00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:35.466


26
00:01:35.466 --> 00:01:40.866
Review the script and output locations. Choose the authentication approach.

27
00:01:40.866 --> 00:01:42.066


28
00:01:42.066 --> 00:01:48.266
Then check the generated command before you use it. Mini-Kitchen is not running the export.

29
00:01:48.266 --> 00:01:49.499


30
00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:55.266
It is not connecting to your tenant. And it is not collecting credentials or secrets.

31
00:01:55.266 --> 00:01:56.499


32
00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:01.866
It is helping you build the command so you can review it, copy it, and run PAX yourself.

33
00:02:01.866 --> 00:02:03.032


34
00:02:03.033 --> 00:02:07.966
Users still need the right permissions when they run PAX, just like any tenant data export.

35
00:02:07.966 --> 00:02:09.199


36
00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:15.366
When the command is ready, the recipe does not have to be a one-time setup. Mini-Kitchen can save

37
00:02:15.366 --> 00:02:21.466
recipes in your browser. You can export a portable .paxlite file. And

38
00:02:21.466 --> 00:02:21.499


39
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:27.800
you can import that file later to reuse or share the recipe setup. That makes repeatable

40
00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:34.366
export workflows easier to rebuild, review, and standardize. And when you need scheduling,

41
00:02:34.366 --> 00:02:40.632
automation, run history, and managed local workflows, those recipes can grow into the full PAX Cookbook

42
00:02:40.633 --> 00:02:40.666


43
00:02:40.666 --> 00:02:46.666
app. PAX Cookbook Mini-Kitchen. A guided path from the data you need to

44
00:02:46.666 --> 00:02:46.866


45
00:02:46.866 --> 00:02:53.199
the PAX command you can run. Browser-only. Free and open source.

46
00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:54.466


47
00:02:54.466 --> 00:03:00.899
Published through Microsoft on GitHub. Start at PAXcookbook.com/Mini-Kitchen.

